62. Livi scriptoris ab aeva] T. Livim Andronicus is spoken of by Quintilian as the first Roman poet, and without much respect:—“ Quid erat futurum si nemo plus effedsset eo quem sequebatur? Nihil iu poetis supra Livium Andronicum, nihil in historiis supra Pontificum annales habe- remus” (x. 2. 7). The date of his birth is uncertain, but he flourished in the middle of the third century n.c., and died A.u.c. 633, or thereabouts. His first play was represented the year before Ennius was born, A.u.c. 514, as Cicero says on the authority of Ennius (Brutus, c. 18). He also says this was the first play put upon the stage (all before had been extempore performanoes). He is said to have been
